      "label": "Transcript",
      "value": "[Page One]\nWashington\n3rd July 1844\nMy dear sir,\nI have entire confidence \nin your friendship and [illegible] \nand shall always receive with \nattention any suggestion, or advice \nyou may favor me with. \nNo one can be more deeply \nimpressed with the magnitude\nof the present crisis, than I am;\nor be more disposed to make sa- \ncrafices to merit it. As long as \nI have served the publick and \nas desireous as I am to spend \nthe rest of my days in quiet [and] re-\ntirement, I shall not hesitate \nto remain [at my post], and do better for our \nprinciples and the safety of the South\n[Page Two]\nand the Union, so long as there \nis a prospect, that I can be of \nany [strikeout] substantial service \nto the great cause. As to the sug- \ngestion in the article you enclosed \nin reference to the gubernatorial claims, \nI must beg to be excused. It is a \npost of high honor, but in no respect \nwould suit me. If I can be of \nany service to the cause, it would \nbe in another sphere. \nI am rejoiced to see the people \nof the state [and] South so much live\nto their true intent. We [illegible] \nUnion [illegible] ourselves to redrop[?]\nall our wrongs. If we could better[?] \nthe South, anything we desire could \nbe effected; and I am happy to say, \nthat there is now a better prospect \nof Union, than there has been \nsince the election of Sen Jackson \n[Page Three]\nin 1828. I regard the defeat of WV\nBuren’s [illegible] and the protection[?]\nof his wing of the party, a great step \ntowards it. They have been the real \ncause of the corruption, and defeat \nand distrust of the party.  They kept\nus divided and the Rob[?] party under \ndictation by party masking and drill.\nAmong its first fruits, I place the \nchange of tone in the Richmond En-\nquirer [and] the polticks of Virginia. So \nlong as the war hitched to the\nN. Jon Cav, through the influence\nof the Enquirer, it was improbable\nto limite the South, or to make \nany decided assistance to the [illegible] – \n[illegible] and abuses of the federal government. \nAnother and fresh cause operating to \nlimite us is the Zenan[?] question. It will  \ndo more to break down the army forts\nin the south and west, then any event \nthat has accused for many years. \nIt is also doing much to unite the \nsouth and west. Their union would \ngain them a preponderance in \n[Page Four]\nthe government, and be followed by a\nrevolution in our politicks, of a \nhighly selecting Charleston.\nThis thinking, I am not [disproved?] to\nencourage any seperate action, at \nthis time, on the part of the state or \nthe South. I am of the impression, \nthat it is the worst moment, that \ncould be selected to make any [illegible]. \nIt would weaken us greatly in other \nquarters on the Zenian[?] question; it \nwould endanger the election of Polk \nand strengthen the prospect of Clay, and lose\nin the control hereafter, can that\nparty succeed. If worse than \nPolk, if he should be elected, back \ninto the hands of the V. B. wing of \nthe party, and, if Clay should be elected, \nit would give the same wing \nthe lead in opposition to his admini-\nstration. It would, in a word, place\nus in a minority of the party, let what \nwill happen.\nWith this impression, I am of the opin\nion, that our true course at present is \nto do nothing, that may tend to the top of\nTexas or to weaken the hold we have \non the party.                                                                                               \nYours truly\nJ.[John] C.[Caldwell] Calhoun\nH.[Henry] W.[Workman] Conner Sr."
